---
import CaseStudy from "@/layouts/case-study.astro"
import { getProject } from "@/data/projects"

const project = getProject("creative-printing-job-submission-portal")!
---

<CaseStudy
  project={project}
  title="Creative Printing Job Submission Portal"
  description="Replaced a high-dropoff, desktop-only print submission path with a responsive icon-grid portal that mapped client project intents directly to the correct print specifications."
  seoTitle="Creative Printing Job Submission Portal · UX Redesign"
  seoDescription="Redesigning a commercial print submission portal with responsive icon-grid navigation, clearer information architecture, and a direct path from project type to job submission."
>
  <h2>Overview</h2>
  <p>
    Commercial print shops survive on speed. The Creative Printing portal where
    customers submitted files and job specs was desktop-only, cluttered with
    unrelated marketing, and hid essential forms deep within nested menus.
  </p>
  <p>
    I redesigned and built the portal to turn a fragmented flow into an
    intuitive, task-based experience. By introducing a responsive,
    mobile-optimized icon grid and grouping entry paths by print type, we
    cleared the friction between a customer’s files and the print queue.
  </p>

  <h2>The Friction in the Flow</h2>
  <p>
    Customers arriving at the portal had one goal: upload files and specify
    dimensions, paper stock, and finishing options. Instead, they faced a wall
    of generic marketing text.
  </p>
  <p>The old system had critical issues:</p>
  <ul>
    <li>
      <strong>Buried forms.</strong> High-value request forms—wide-format blueprints,
      booklet bindings, vinyl banner specs—were scattered across deep page levels,
      forcing customers to guess which link led to the right form.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Zero mobile support.</strong> Contractors on job sites and designers
      on the move could not submit files from their phones. Fields broke, and file
      uploads timed out on mobile viewports.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Form fatigue.</strong> Redundant fields asked for the same contact information
      on every page instead of caching customer details.
    </li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Refactoring the Information Architecture</h2>
  <p>
    I restructured the portal’s landing page around immediate customer intent.
    We identified the five highest-volume print categories and surfaced them as
    high-contrast, touch-friendly icon-grid targets on the homepage.
  </p>
  <p>
    The design prioritizes action: instead of reading service lists, a user taps
    "Wide Format," "Brochures & Booklets," or "General Upload." That choice
    instantly routes them to a dedicated form with pre-configured print
    specifications. Unrelated options are suppressed, keeping the interface
    clean and the mental load low.
  </p>

  <h2>Responsive Design and Implementation</h2>
  <p>
    I built the interface to scale fluidly from small screens to large desktop
    monitors. Inputs use large, accessible touch targets, the file-drop zone
    supports native mobile camera and file-system uploads, and live file-size
    validation lets users know if an upload is too heavy before submitting.
  </p>
  <p>
    I also designed and built 20+ WordPress client sites, working directly with
    each client to wireframe layouts, establish clear navigation, and refine the
    experience through feedback-driven iterations.
  </p>

  <h2>Outcomes</h2>
  <p>
    The redesigned portal went live as the primary gateway for Creative
    Printing’s commercial accounts. By replacing a buried desktop flow with a
    responsive, intent-mapped icon grid, we resolved the main source of customer
    submission friction. The new design eliminated complaints about “missing”
    forms, minimized phone support queries, and established a modern,
    mobile-friendly standard for the shop’s web operations.
  </p>
</CaseStudy>
